### Model

The explanation for this issue is straightforward!

When the chunking engine (added earlier) compresses 1800 uncompressed 1-second samples down to approximately 450 summary points by summarizing every 4 items into 1 larger item, the physical spacing of the resulting timestamps inherently moves further apart. The resulting points were separated from each other by around 4 seconds (as expected!).

However, there was an existing function in [app.js](app.js:0:0-0:0) designed to monitor network disconnections by dropping "invisible gaps" into graphs if data stops arriving on schedule. Because the backend was still branding the HTTP response exactly as `"1s"` resolution, the frontend chart engine expected every single point to be 1000ms apart. When it saw your points spaced by 4000ms apart, it assumed there was a network dropout and aggressively inserted a `null` visual gap between literally every single point, leaving the graph visually empty (yet technically full of valid underlying data).

I resolved this on both ends:
1. **Dynamic Res Strings in the Backend:** Updated the chunk-cruncher inside [store.go](store.go:0:0-0:0) to rewrite the metadata label to `"4s"`, `"2m"`, etc., mathematically proportional out of the loop block size.
2. **Dynamic Gap Parsing in the Frontend:** Changed the [insertGapsInHistory](app.js:1275:4-1302:5) engine inside [app.js](app.js:0:0-0:0) to strip and read the integer properties dynamically. It now inherently supports ANY resolution structure rather than a hardcoded lookup map.

Your charts should now render continuously grouped lines correctly across all timeframes. I've re-built the binary successfully for you.

